.SH "Detailed Description"
.PP 
""_hex is a compile-time user-defined literal returning a \fRstd::array<std::byte>\fP, equivalent to \fBParseHex()\fP\&. Variants provided:

.PP
.IP "\(bu" 2
""_hex_v: Returns \fRstd::vector<std::byte>\fP, useful for heap allocation or variable-length serialization\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
""_hex_u8: Returns \fRstd::array<uint8_t>\fP, for cases where \fRstd::byte\fP is incompatible\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
""_hex_v_u8: Returns \fRstd::vector<uint8_t>\fP, combining heap allocation with \fRuint8_t\fP\&.
.PP

.PP
\fBWarning\fP
.RS 4
It could be necessary to use vector instead of array variants when serializing, or vice versa, because vectors are assumed to be variable- length and serialized with a size prefix, while arrays are considered fixed length and serialized with no prefix\&.

.PP
It may be preferable to use vector variants to save stack space when declaring local variables if hex strings are large\&. Alternatively variables could be declared constexpr to avoid using stack space\&.

.PP
Avoid \fRuint8_t\fP variants when not necessary, as the codebase migrates to use \fRstd::byte\fP instead of \fRunsigned char\fP and \fRuint8_t\fP\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBNote\fP
.RS 4
One reason ""_hex uses \fRstd::array\fP instead of \fRstd::vector\fP like \fBParseHex()\fP does is because heap-based containers cannot cross the compile- time/runtime barrier\&. 
.RE
.PP

